The exponential function, denoted by $\exp x$, is defined for all $x \in \mathbb{R}$ by the power series:
\begin{equation*}
\exp x = \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{x^n}{n!} = 1 + x + \frac{x^2}{2!} + \frac{x^3}{3!} + \cdots
\end{equation*}

The hyperbolic cosecant function, $\operatorname{csch} x$, has a Taylor series expansion given by:
\begin{align*}
\operatorname{csch} x &= \sum_{n = 0}^\infty \frac {2 \left(1 - 2^{2 n - 1}\right) B_{2 n} \, x^{2 n - 1} } {(2 n)!} \\
&= \frac 1 x - \frac x 6 + \frac {7 x^3} {360} - \frac {31 x^5} {15 \, 120} + \cdots
\end{align*}
where $B_n$ denotes the Bernoulli numbers. This series converges for $0 < |x| < \pi$.

