Let $(S, \circ)$ be a monoid with identity element $e_S$. If an element $x \in S$ possesses both a left inverse $x_L$ (i.e., there exists $x_L \in S$ such that $x_L \circ x = e_S$) and a right inverse $x_R$ (i.e., there exists $x_R \in S$ such that $x \circ x_R = e_S$), then $x_L = x_R$. This common element is the unique inverse of $x$, being its sole left and right inverse.
