Let $b \in \mathbb{Z}$ be an integer such that $b > 1$. For every $n \in \mathbb{Z}_{>0}$, there exists a unique finite sequence of integers $(r_j)_{j=0}^t$ such that:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $n = \sum_{k=0}^t r_k b^k$;
    \item For all $k$ such that $0 \le k \le t$, $0 \le r_k < b$;
    \item $r_t \ne 0$.
\end{enumerate}
This unique sequence $(r_j)_{j=0}^t$ is called the \textbf{base-$b$ representation of $n$}, and $n$ is said to be \textbf{written in base $b$}.

